    <h1>The Controller Layer in Web Applications</h1>
    <p>In an ASP.NET Core web application, the <strong>Controller Layer</strong> is responsible for handling user requests, interacting with the business logic or service layer, and returning the appropriate response (HTML, JSON, etc.).</p>

    <h2>Why the Controller Layer is Important</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Acts as the bridge between the user interface (views) and the data/business logic.</li>
        <li>Organizes your application by separating responsibilities.</li>
        <li>Makes your code easier to maintain and test.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Example: Simple Controller</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">HomeController Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class HomeController : Controller
{
    // Action method for the homepage
    public IActionResult Index()
    {
        // You could get data from a service or repository here
        ViewData["Message"] = "Welcome to the Controller Layer Example!";
        return View();
    }

    // Action method for About page
    public IActionResult About()
    {
        ViewData["Message"] = "This is the About page";
        return View();
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>How it Works</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Each public method in a controller is called an <strong>action</strong> and can respond to a user request.</li>
        <li>The controller can access models, services, or repositories to get or manipulate data.</li>
        <li>It then returns a response, often a <code>View()</code> or <code>Json()</code>, which the browser can display.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Exercise</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Create a controller named <code>ProductsController</code>.</li>
        <li>Add two actions: <code>List()</code> to show all products and <code>Details(int id)</code> to show a single product.</li>
        <li>Use <code>ViewData</code> or <code>ViewBag</code> to send some example product information to the views.</li>
        <li>Test the actions by navigating to the corresponding URLs in your browser.</li>
    </ul>

